div1.p:
It is the duty of the living thus to provide for the dead.
It is not a mere office of pious regard for others;
but it comes home to our own bosoms, as those who are soon to enter upon the common inheritance.

Poetry has told us this truth in lines of transcendant beauty and force, which find a response in every breast:--
For who, to dumb forgetfulness a prey,
This pleasing, anxious being e'er resigned,
Left the warm precincts of the cheerful day,
Nor cast one longing, lingering look behind?
On some fond breast the parting soul relies;
Some pious drops the closing eye requires;
E'en from the tomb the voice of Nature cries;
E'en in our ashes live their wonted fires.

div2.p:
Where in this world, indeed!
repeated Lilias Fay;
and being faint and weary, the more so by the heaviness of her heart, the Lily drooped her head and sat down on the summit of a knoll, repeating, where in this world shall we build our Temple!
